<subSubSection id="44C472C38640C3522FCAA211197DF75F" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="0C6121488640C3522FCAA211194BF7AC" blockId="10.[1974,2563,1877,2300]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis id="3EAAFD5A8640C3522FCAA211180CF880" bold="true" box="[1975,2130,1877,1906]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="CBDE5ACB8640C352201AA2111916F868" authority="M. G. M. van Roosmalen et al., 2002" authorityName="M. G. M. van Roosmalen" authorityYear="2002" class="Mammalia" family="Pitheciidae" genus="Callicebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bernhardi">Callicebus bernhardi M. G. M. van Roosmalen et al., 2002</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="BCB62B158640C3522122A2C5194BF7AC" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3806466331" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">outskirts of the Nova Olinda settlement on the left (west) bank of the Rio Aripuana, 41 km south-west of the town of Novo Aripuana, in the Brazilian state of Amazonas (05° 30r 63” 8, 60°24 61” W).</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C6121488640C3522FC7AD2D197DF75F" blockId="10.[1974,2563,1877,2300]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">
<taxonomicName id="CBDE5ACB8640C3522FC7AD2D1807F774" authorityName="M. G. M. van Roosmalen" box="[1978,2137,2153,2182]" class="Mammalia" family="Pitheciidae" genus="Callicebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bernhardi">C. bernhardi</taxonomicName>
is a member of the 
<taxonomicName id="CBDE5ACB8640C35221F9AD2D1A5EF774" baseAuthorityName="Hoffmannsegg" baseAuthorityYear="1807" box="[2436,2560,2153,2182]" class="Mammalia" family="Pitheciidae" genus="Callicebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="moloch">C. moloch</taxonomicName>
species group. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="44C472C38640C3522FCBADF8176BF665" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" type="distribution">
<caption id="58A171C08640C3522FCBADF8176BF665" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6632335" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6632335" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6632335/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" targetBox="[1362,1941,1886,2292]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph id="0C6121488640C3522FCBADF8176BF665" blockId="10.[1974,2563,1877,2300]" lastBlockId="10.[1355,2561,2309,3281]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis id="3EAAFD5A8640C3522FCBADF8183BF727" bold="true" box="[1974,2149,2236,2261]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">Distribution.</emphasis>
S Brazilian Amazon Basin, S of the right (S) bank of the Rio Madeira, E of the lower Rio Jiparana and W to the rios Aripuana and Roosevelt; S limits of its distribution are unclear, but there may be a zone of contact or intergradation with the ranges of the Ashy Titi (
<taxonomicName id="CBDE5ACB8640C3522ED9AC101706F683" authorityName="Spix" authorityYear="1823" box="[1700,1880,2388,2417]" class="Mammalia" family="Pitheciidae" genus="Callicebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="10" pageNumber="459" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cinerascens">C. cinerascens</taxonomicName>
) and the White-eared Titi (
<taxonomicName id="CBDE5ACB8640C352209FAC1019EFF683" authorityName="d'Orbigny" authorityYear="1836" baseAuthorityName="d'Orbigny" box="[2274,2481,2388,2417]" class="Mammalia" family="Pitheciidae" genus="Callicebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="donacophilus">C. donacophilus</taxonomicName>
) in S Rondonia or N Mato Grosso states.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="44C472C38640C3522D33ACDA1730F5AE" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" type="description">
<paragraph id="0C6121488640C3522D33ACDA19A2F5FC" blockId="10.[1355,2561,2309,3281]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis id="3EAAFD5A8640C3522D33ACDA161BF64D" bold="true" box="[1358,1605,2462,2495]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 36-38 cm,tail ¢.55 cm; weight 700-1200 g. Prince Bernhard’s Titi is grayish-black above and on limbs, mixed with brownish-agouti or rustbrown on back. Underparts, inner surfaces of limbs, cheeks, and chin are dark orange.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C6121488640C3522D33AF5D1730F5AE" blockId="10.[1355,2561,2309,3281]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">Face is black, as are ears, having conspicuous whitish tufts. Hands and feet are silverywhite, and tail is black, with a white tip.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="44C472C38640C3522D30AF2715EDF523" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="0C6121488640C3522D30AF2715EDF523" blockId="10.[1355,2561,2309,3281]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis id="3EAAFD5A8640C3522D30AF2715E1F576" bold="true" box="[1357,1471,2659,2692]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">Habitat.</emphasis>
Lowland terra firma rainforest. Groups of Prince Bernhard’s Titis have been observed primarily in secondary and disturbed forest habitats and even rubber plantations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="44C472C38640C3522D30AF9C1950F50B" box="[1357,2318,2776,2809]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph id="0C6121488640C3522D30AF9C1950F50B" blockId="10.[1355,2561,2309,3281]" box="[1357,2318,2776,2809]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis id="3EAAFD5A8640C3522D30AF9C160CF50B" bold="true" box="[1357,1618,2776,2809]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
There is no information available for this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="44C472C38640C3522D30AE44158FF49C" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="0C6121488640C3522D30AE44158FF49C" blockId="10.[1355,2561,2309,3281]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">
<emphasis id="3EAAFD5A8640C3522D30AE44158DF4D3" bold="true" box="[1357,1491,2816,2849]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467">Breeding.</emphasis>
There is no specific information available for this species, but all titis form monogamous breeding pairs. The male provides parental care by carrying the single offspring.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="44C472C38640C3522D36AE3D18ACF464" box="[1355,2290,2937,2966]" pageId="10" pageNumber="467" type="activity">
